"Here is a new Python coding question for you:\n\n{\n    \"title\": \"Hardest Level (Hard)\",\n    \"description\": \"Write a function `hardest_level` that takes as input the difficulty of a level (`easy`, `medium`, or `hard`) and returns the corresponding number of stars. The function should use a dictionary to map difficulty levels to star counts.\\n\\n#### Function Signature\\n```python\\ndef hardest_level(difficulty: str) -> int:\\n```\\n\\n#### Input\\n- `difficulty` (str): Either `easy`, `medium`, or `hard`.\\n\\n#### Output\\n- Returns the number of stars corresponding to the given difficulty level.\\n\",\n    \"code\": \"\"\"\nimport string\n\ndef hardest_level(difficulty: str) -> int:\n    # Create a dictionary mapping difficulty levels to star counts\n    difficulty_levels = {\"easy\": 1, \"medium\": 2, \"hard\": 3}\n\n    # Check if the input difficulty is valid\n    if difficulty not in difficulty_levels:\n        raise ValueError(\"Invalid difficulty level\")\n\n    # Return the number of stars corresponding to the given difficulty level\n    return difficulty_levels[difficulty]\n    \"\"\",\n    \"tests\": [\n        \"assert hardest_level('easy') == 1\",\n        \"assert hardest_level('medium') == 2\",\n        \"assert hardest_level('hard') == 3\",\n        \"assert hardest_level('foo') == 0\"  # Invalid input should raise an error\n    ]\n}"